\f0\b \cf2 Socrates' Proposal for his Sentence
\f1\b0 \'a0\
\
There are many reasons why I am not grieved, O men of Athens, at\'a0the vote of condemnation. I expected it, and am only surprised that the\'a0votes are so nearly equal; for I had thought that the majority against\'a0me would have been far larger; but now, had thirty votes gone over to the\'a0other side, I should have been acquitted. And I may say that I have escaped\'a0Meletus. And I may say more; for without the assistance of Anytus and Lycon,\'a0he would not have had a fifth part of the votes, as the law requires, in\'a0which case he would have incurred a fine of a thousand drachmae, as is\'a0evident.\'a0\
\
And so he proposes death as the penalty. And what shall I propose\'a0on my part, O men of Athens? Clearly that which is my due. And what is\'a0that which I ought to pay or to receive? What shall be done to the man\'a0who has never had the wit to be idle during his whole life; but has been\'a0careless of what the many care about - wealth, and family interests, and\'a0military offices, and speaking in the assembly, and magistracies, and plots,\'a0and parties. Reflecting that I was really too honest a man to follow in\'a0this way and live, I did not go where I could do no good to you or to myself;\'a0but where I could do the greatest good privately to everyone of you, thither\'a0I went, and sought to persuade every man among you that he must look to\'a0himself, and seek virtue and wisdom before he looks to his private interests,\'a0and look to the state before he looks to the interests of the state; and\'a0that this should be the order which he observes in all his actions. What\'a0shall be done to such a one? Doubtless some good thing, O men of Athens,\'a0if he has his reward; and the good should be of a kind suitable to him.\'a0What would be a reward suitable to a poor man who is your benefactor, who\'a0desires leisure that he may instruct you? There can be no more fitting\'a0reward than maintenance in the Prytaneum, O men of Athens, a reward which\'a0he deserves far more than the citizen who has won the prize at Olympia\'a0in the horse or chariot race, whether the chariots were drawn by two horses\'a0or by many. For I am in want, and he has enough; and he only gives youthe appearance of happiness, and I give you the reality. And if I am to\'a0estimate the penalty justly, I say that maintenance in the Prytaneum is\'a0the just return.\'a0\
\
Perhaps you may think that I am braving you in saying this, as\'a0in what I said before about the tears and prayers. But that is not the\'a0case. I speak rather because I am convinced that I never intentionally\'a0wronged anyone, although I cannot convince you of that - for we have had\'a0a short conversation only; but if there were a law at Athens, such as there\'a0is in other cities, that a capital cause should not be decided in one day,\'a0then I believe that I should have convinced you; but now the time is too\'a0short. I cannot in a moment refute great slanders; and, as I am convinced\'a0that I never wronged another, I will assuredly not wrong myself. I will\'a0not say of myself that I deserve any evil, or propose any penalty. Why\'a0should I? Because I am afraid of the penalty of death which Meletus proposes?\'a0When I do not know whether death is a good or an evil, why should I propose\'a0a penalty which would certainly be an evil? Shall I say imprisonment? And\'a0why should I live in prison, and be the slave of the magistrates of the\'a0year - of the Eleven? Or shall the penalty be a fine, and imprisonment\'a0until the fine is paid? There is the same objection. I should have to lie\'a0in prison, for money I have none, and I cannot pay. And if I say exile\'a0(and this may possibly be the penalty which you will affix), I must indeed\'a0be blinded by the love of life if I were to consider that when you, who\'a0are my own citizens, cannot endure my discourses and words, and have found\'a0them so grievous and odious that you would fain have done with them, others\'a0are likely to endure me. No, indeed, men of Athens, that is not very likely.\'a0And what a life should I lead, at my age, wandering from city to city,\'a0living in ever-changing exile, and always being driven out! For I am quite\'a0sure that into whatever place I go, as here so also there, the young men\'a0will come to me; and if I drive them away, their elders will drive me out\'a0at their desire: and if I let them come, their fathers and friends will\'a0drive me out for their sakes.\'a0\
\
Someone will say: Yes, Socrates, but cannot you hold your tongue,\'a0and then you may go into a foreign city, and no one will interfere with\'a0you? Now I have great difficulty in making you understand my answer to\'a0this. For if I tell you that this would be a disobedience to a divine command,\'a0and therefore that I cannot hold my tongue, you will not believe that I\'a0am serious; and if I say again that the greatest good of man is daily to\'a0converse about virtue, and all that concerning which you hear me examining\'a0myself and others, and that the life which is unexamined is not worth living\'a0- that you are still less likely to believe. And yet what I say is true,\'a0although a thing of which it is hard for me to persuade you. Moreover,\'a0I am not accustomed to think that I deserve any punishment. Had I money\'a0I might have proposed to give you what I had, and have been none the worse.\'a0But you see that I have none, and can only ask you to proportion the fine\'a0to my means. However, I think that I could afford a minae, and therefore\'a0I propose that penalty; Plato, Crito, Critobulus, and Apollodorus, my friends\'a0here, bid me say thirty minae, and they will be the sureties. Well then,\'a0say thirty minae, let that be the penalty; for that they will be ample\'a0security to you.\'a0\
\
