\f0\b \cf2 Socrates' Comments on his Sentence
\f1\b0 \'a0\
\
Not much time will be gained, O Athenians, in return for the evil\'a0name which you will get from the detractors of the city, who will say that\'a0you killed Socrates, a wise man; for they will call me wise even although\'a0I am not wise when they want to reproach you. If you had waited a little\'a0while, your desire would have been fulfilled in the course of nature. For\'a0I am far advanced in years, as you may perceive, and not far from death.\'a0I am speaking now only to those of you who have condemned me to death.\'a0And I have another thing to say to them: You think that I was convicted\'a0through deficiency of words - I mean, that if I had thought fit to leave\'a0nothing undone, nothing unsaid, I might have gained an acquittal. Not so;\'a0the deficiency which led to my conviction was not of words - certainly\'a0not. But I had not the boldness or impudence or inclination to address\'a0you as you would have liked me to address you, weeping and wailing and\'a0lamenting, and saying and doing many things which you have been accustomed\'a0to hear from others, and which, as I say, are unworthy of me. But I thought\'a0that I ought not to do anything common or mean in the hour of danger: nor\'a0do I now repent of the manner of my defence, and I would rather die having\'a0spoken after my manner, than speak in your manner and live. For neither\'a0in war nor yet at law ought any man to use every way of escaping death.\'a0For often in battle there is no doubt that if a man will throw away his\'a0arms, and fall on his knees before his pursuers, he may escape death; and\'a0in other dangers there are other ways of escaping death, if a man is willing\'a0to say and do anything. The difficulty, my friends, is not in avoiding\'a0death, but in avoiding unrighteousness; for that runs faster than death.\'a0I am old and move slowly, and the slower runner has overtaken me, and my\'a0accusers are keen and quick, and the faster runner, who is unrighteousness,\'a0has overtaken them. And now I depart hence condemned by you to suffer the\'a0penalty of death, and they, too, go their ways condemned by the truth to\'a0suffer the penalty of villainy and wrong; and I must abide by my award\'a0- let them abide by theirs. I suppose that these things may be regarded\'a0as fated, - and I think that they are well.\'a0\
\
And now, O men who have condemned me, I would fain prophesy to\'a0you; for I am about to die, and that is the hour in which men are gifted\'a0with prophetic power. And I prophesy to you who are my murderers, that\'a0immediately after my death punishment far heavier than you have inflicted\'a0on me will surely await you. Me you have killed because you wanted to escape\'a0the accuser, and not to give an account of your lives. But that will not\'a0be as you suppose: far otherwise. For I say that there will be more accusers\'a0of you than there are now; accusers whom hitherto I have restrained: and\'a0as they are younger they will be more severe with you, and you will be\'a0more offended at them. For if you think that by killing men you can avoid\'a0the accuser censuring your lives, you are mistaken; that is not a way of\'a0escape which is either possible or honorable; the easiest and noblest way\'a0is not to be crushing others, but to be improving yourselves. This is the\'a0prophecy which I utter before my departure, to the judges who have condemned\'a0me.\'a0\
\
Friends, who would have acquitted me, I would like also to talk\'a0with you about this thing which has happened, while the magistrates are\'a0busy, and before I go to the place at which I must die. Stay then awhile,\'a0for we may as well talk with one another while there is time. You are my\'a0friends, and I should like to show you the meaning of this event which\'a0has happened to me. O my judges - for you I may truly call judges - I should\'a0like to tell you of a wonderful circumstance. Hitherto the familiar oracle\'a0within me has constantly been in the habit of opposing me even about trifles,\'a0if I was going to make a slip or error about anything; and now as you see\'a0there has come upon me that which may be thought, and is generally believed\'a0to be, the last and worst evil. But the oracle made no sign of opposition,\'a0either as I was leaving my house and going out in the morning, or when\'a0I was going up into this court, or while I was speaking, at anything which\'a0I was going to say; and yet I have often been stopped in the middle ofa speech; but now in nothing I either said or did touching this matter\'a0has the oracle opposed me. What do I take to be the explanation of this?\'a0I will tell you. I regard this as a proof that what has happened to me\'a0is a good, and that those of us who think that death is an evil are in\'a0error. This is a great proof to me of what I am saying, for the customary\'a0sign would surely have opposed me had I been going to evil and not to\'a0good.\'a0\
\
Let us reflect in another way, and we shall see that there is great\'a0reason to hope that death is a good, for one of two things: - either death\'a0is a state of nothingness and utter unconsciousness, or, as men say, there\'a0is a change and migration of the soul from this world to another. Now if\'a0you suppose that there is no consciousness, but a sleep like the sleep\'a0of him who is undisturbed even by the sight of dreams, death will be an\'a0unspeakable gain. For if a person were to select the night in which his\'a0sleep was undisturbed even by dreams, and were to compare with this the\'a0other days and nights of his life, and then were to tell us how many days\'a0and nights he had passed in the course of his life better and more pleasantly\'a0than this one, I think that any man, I will not say a private man, but\'a0even the great king, will not find many such days or nights, when compared\'a0with the others. Now if death is like this, I say that to die is gain;\'a0for eternity is then only a single night. But if death is the journey to\'a0another place, and there, as men say, all the dead are, what good, O my\'a0friends and judges, can be greater than this? If indeed when the pilgrim\'a0arrives in the world below, he is delivered from the professors of justice\'a0in this world, and finds the true judges who are said to give judgment\'a0there, Minos and Rhadamanthus and Aeacus and Triptolemus, and other sonsof God who were righteous in their own life, that pilgrimage will be worth\'a0making. What would not a man give if he might converse with Orpheus and\'a0Musaeus and Hesiod and Homer? Nay, if this be true, let me die again and\'a0again. I, too, shall have a wonderful interest in a place where I can converse\'a0with Palamedes, and Ajax the son of Telamon, and other heroes of old, who\'a0have suffered death through an unjust judgment; and there will be no small\'a0pleasure, as I think, in comparing my own sufferings with theirs. Above\'a0all, I shall be able to continue my search into true and false knowledge;\'a0as in this world, so also in that; I shall find out who is wise, and who\'a0pretends to be wise, and is not. What would not a man give, O judges, to\'a0be able to examine the leader of the great Trojan expedition; or Odysseus\'a0or Sisyphus, or numberless others, men and women too! What infinite delight\'a0would there be in conversing with them and asking them questions! For in\'a0that world they do not put a man to death for this; certainly not. For\'a0besides being happier in that world than in this, they will be immortal,\'a0if what is said is true.\'a0\
\
Wherefore, O judges, be of good cheer about death, and know this\'a0of a truth - that no evil can happen to a good man, either in life or after\'a0death. He and his are not neglected by the gods; nor has my own approaching\'a0end happened by mere chance. But I see clearly that to die and be released\'a0was better for me; and therefore the oracle gave no sign. For which reason\'a0also, I am not angry with my accusers, or my condemners; they have done\'a0me no harm, although neither of them meant to do me any good; and for this\'a0I may gently blame them.\'a0\
\
Still I have a favor to ask of them. When my sons are grown up,\'a0I would ask you, O my friends, to punish them; and I would have you trouble\'a0them, as I have troubled you, if they seem to care about riches, or anything,\'a0more than about virtue; or if they pretend to be something when they are\'a0really nothing, - then reprove them, as I have reproved you, for not caring\'a0about that for which they ought to care, and thinking that they are something\'a0when they are really nothing. And if you do this, I and my sons will have\'a0received justice at your hands.\'a0\
\
The hour of departure has arrived, and we go our ways - I to die,\'a0and you to live. Which is better God only knows.\'a0\
